    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "yo i was doing some sprints today and my legs felt like they were on fire lol. can u explain what actually happens with the lactic acid when u push that hard? like how does it get made and how does it go away?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "That burning feeling is due to the rapid production of lactate when your muscles demand more energy than oxygen can supply. During intense exercise, your body switches to anaerobic respiration, converting glucose into lactate as a byproduct. The lactate itself doesn't cause the burn; it's the associated metabolic byproducts that contribute to acidity. Your body then manages this by shuttling lactate to other tissues to be converted back into usable energy through the Cori cycle.",
      "source": "target",
